The large macroeconomic divergence
PARIS – "Global expansion has reached its peak," warns the OECD in its latest Economic Outlook, and performance could suffer if downward risks materialize.
The party is not yet over: it is expected that global growth will continue in the years 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
Yet economists are notoriously bad at recognizing macroeconomic turning points, and the future economic course is hard to assess.
Possible stumbling blocks are numerous: more aggressive monetary tightening, particularly in the United States; further escalation of protectionism; an economic landing in China that turns out to be harsher than expected; and a return of tensions in the Eurozone, triggered by concerns regarding the fate of Italian public finances.
All of this or even each of these developments could intensify the downturn that has already begun.
A recession in the USA would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is already looking ahead to his re-election in 2020, although such a development would not contradict known patterns.
Officially, the expansion began in June 2009, and with a duration until July 2019, it would be the longest such phase in the economic history of the USA.
Unemployment is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, the implementation of the economic policy measures of the Trump administration, consisting of massive tax cuts and increased spending - thus a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was intended to avert an impending depression - is not economically sensible.
In order, the Federal Reserve central bank is left with only two options: either it raises interest rates more drastically in order to offset the poorly timed expansionary measures, or it capitulates.
Such a reckless coward's game between American fiscal and monetary authorities increases the risk of instability in the rest of the world, considering the global effects of the US interest rate cycle.
A global recession would come more than too early for those countries where recovery started late or was weak, or both.
An extreme example is Greece, where growth only picked up in 2017 and unemployment is still almost 20 percent.
But Greece is not alone.
In Italy, the per capita GDP is no higher than in the mid-1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment is still significantly above pre-crisis levels.
The challenge is to bring long-term unemployed people, who face the risk of skill erosion, back into employment.
To prevent lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international situation alone cannot solve their problems, but it would help maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is the German labor market, which is currently in a far better condition than in 2007.
Full employment prevails in the western federal states and economic growth is increasingly dependent on immigration: in 2017, the net inflow – not refugees, but immigrants from other European countries – amounted to around 400,000 people.
In Japan, the United Kingdom, and Poland, the recovery was also characterized by the creation of many jobs.
Citizens complain about income, inequality, or rising house prices, but not about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis affected almost all developed economies at the same time.
Today, however, they do not appear either structurally or cyclically on a single line.
This is certainly alarming, as the emerging cooling of the world economy comes at a time of increasing political fragility.
Trust in governments and institutions of political decision-making is – understandably – extremely low.
Collective economic mismanagement would only further undermine this trust and fuel the already rising economic nationalism.
What is to be done now?
The list of tasks to be tackled starts in one's own country. In many countries where the labor market remains out of balance, national measures are needed to strengthen economic potential and improve access to jobs.
In France, employers report a shortage of skilled workers despite an unemployment rate of 9 percent and reforms by President Emmanuel Macron.
To change this, comprehensive measures in the education sector are just as necessary as support for mobility, incentives for accepting jobs, and the opening up of protected sectors.
This is also already happening.
In Italy, on the other hand, the governing coalition has launched a stimulus program and at the same time proposed measures to reduce the labor participation rate.
This includes, for example, the reversal of the 2011 pension reform as well as the introduction of a "citizen's income," which, in the case of inadequate planning or implementation, will lead to fewer people pursuing employment.
This political contradiction and less Italy's deviation from the European Union's budget rules is the real cause for concern.
The second priority is to establish a risk balance.
For some time now, a political debate has been unfolding between political hawks and doves, with the former warning that asset purchases by central banks and interest rates near zero are fueling financial instability and inflation risks. The greatest concern of the doves, however, is deflation.
Both are certainly real, although there is more reason for concern about deflation.
Real estate price bubbles can be contained through regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio of the loan amount to the value of the property or between the loan amount and income.
Regarding inflation, the forecasts are regularly proven wrong.
Wages have so far reacted slowly to the declining unemployment rate.
There is a justified fear of a possible abrupt increase, but after so many years of undershooting inflation, this risk can certainly be taken.
The collective costs of a temporary inflation overshoot pale in comparison to those of an early onset recession, which leads to lasting damage and a political counter-movement against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is by far the most difficult to achieve, especially in the eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a uniform policy for different economies.
The standard recipe would be for the ECB to aim at the average inflation rate and to rely on national fiscal policy for fine-tuning the macroeconomic course.
However, due to higher debt or remaining deficits, exactly those countries that would need further growth are precisely those that do not have any fiscal policy room for maneuver.
Neither Greece nor Italy, not even Spain or France, can currently consider a substantial stimulus program.
Without the possibility of cross-border transfers (which are also not provided for in the recent agreement between France and Germany on a mini-eurozone budget), this is another reason why the ECB should be more daring.
This would leave the governments of countries threatened by overheating with the task of cooling down their economies using fiscal means, while the governments of countries still struggling for economic improvement would be faced with the task of tapping into their economic potential.
There are numerous reasons to doubt that this is possible.
But it is the task of political decision-makers to manage risks, even if the risks of today are not the usual ones.
At stake is the resilience of the world economic system.
Despite favorable conditions, the first cracks are showing.
It has to be prevented that thereby cracks occur.
